2. Bagging

For Bagging, use mtry = p, the number of all predictors.

library(randomForest)
randomForest 4.6-14
Type rfNews() to see new features/changes/bug fixes.
set.seed(769)
(r = randomForest(class ~ ., data=wdbc, mtry=10, importance=TRUE))

Call:

               Type of random forest: classification
                     Number of trees: 500
No. of variables tried at each split: 10

        OOB estimate of  error rate: 6.15%
Confusion matrix:
          benign malignant class.error

3. Random Forests

For Random Forests, use mtry = m, where m < p.

4. Boosting

library(gbm)     # Gradient Boosting Machine
Loaded gbm 2.1.8
set.seed(769)
# use distribution="bernoulli" for a two-class classification problem
wdbc2 = cbind(wdbc, class2=as.integer(wdbc$class)-1)   # requires integer values 
(r = gbm(class2 ~ . - class, data=wdbc2, distribution="bernoulli", n.trees=500, interaction.depth=3))
gbm(formula = class2 ~ . - class, distribution = "bernoulli", 
    data = wdbc2, n.trees = 500, interaction.depth = 3)
A gradient boosted model with bernoulli loss function.
500 iterations were performed.
There were 10 predictors of which 10 had non-zero influence.
